To address your requirement for quantifying the relationship between signals in multiple channels of microscopy images, taking into account existing annotations, I propose building a pipeline that effectively groups these channels based on their annotations. This approach is crucial because it directly aligns with your goal of understanding how signals relate to each other within your images.

The main steps this pipeline will take include first identifying and grouping the incoming data based on the annotations provided. This step is essential as it sets the foundation for subsequent operations that aim to quantify relationships between signals. Following the initial grouping, the pipeline will then apply operations to these groups of annotated channels. These operations could include various mathematical or statistical calculations designed to compare or relate the signals across different channels.

The pipeline will be structured in such a way that it can handle multiple input channels, potentially from different sources or with varying annotations. This capability is vital because it allows for a comprehensive analysis of how signals interact across multiple channels, providing a more nuanced understanding of the data.

The key steps in this process involve first identifying a node capable of grouping incoming data based on annotations, which will serve as the core component of our pipeline. This node should be able to handle multiple input slots, each potentially representing a different channel of an image, and group them accordingly based on their annotations.

